vectorData.altText: 9. Above the arcuate line, the aponeuroses of which muscles contribute to the anterior lamina of the rectus sheath? Choose all that apply.
That's right!  Above the arcuate line, the rectus sheath has an anterior and a posterior lamina. The anterior lamina is formed by aponeuroses of external oblique and internal oblique.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

The rectus sheath is formed by the aponeuroses of the three flat muscles of the anterolateral abdominal wall. 
Along the upper ¾ of the length of the rectus abdominis, the rectus sheath has an anterior and a posterior lamina     . 
The anterior lamina is formed by the aponeurosis of the external oblique, with a contribution from the aponeurosis of the internal oblique.  
The posterior lamina is formed by the aponeurosis of the transversus abdominis with a contribution from the aponeurosis of the internal oblique.
